ls: List files and directories in the current directory.
Example: ls
2. cd: Change the current directory.
Example: cd /home/user/Documents
3. pwd: Print the working directory (current directory).
Example: pwd
4. mkdir: Create a new directory.
Example: mkdir new_folder
5. rm: Remove files or directories.
Example: rm file.txt (removes the file &quot;file.txt&quot;)
Example: rm -r folder (removes the directory &quot;folder&quot; and its contents)
6. cp: Copy files or directories.
Example: cp file.txt /path/to/destination/ (copies &quot;file.txt&quot; to the specified
destination)
7. mv: Move or rename files or directories.
Example: mv file.txt new_name.txt (renames &quot;file.txt&quot; to &quot;new_name.txt&quot;)
Example: mv file.txt /path/to/destination/ (moves &quot;file.txt&quot; to the specified
destination)
8. cat: Concatenate and display file content.
Example: cat file.txt
9. grep: Search for a pattern in a file or output.
Example: grep &quot;keyword&quot; file.txt
10. chmod: Change file permissions.
Example: chmod +x script.sh (gives execute permission to &quot;script.sh&quot;)
11. chown: Change file ownership.
Example: chown user:group file.txt (changes the owner and group of
&quot;file.txt&quot; to specified user and group)

12. ps: Show the current processes.
Example: ps
13. kill: Terminate a process.
Example: kill PID (where PID is the process ID)
14. top: Display real-time system resource usage and running processes.
Example: top
15. tar: Archive files into a tarball.
Example: tar -cvf archive.tar file1 file2 (creates an archive &quot;archive.tar&quot;
with &quot;file1&quot; and &quot;file2&quot;)

16. gzip/gunzip: Compress or decompress files.
Example: gzip file.txt (compresses &quot;file.txt&quot; into &quot;file.txt.gz&quot;) Example: gunzip
file.txt.gz (decompresses &quot;file.txt.gz&quot; back to &quot;file.txt&quot;)
17. ssh: Securely connect to a remote server.
Example: ssh user@hostname (connects to &quot;hostname&quot; as &quot;user&quot;)
18. wget: Download files from the web.
Example: wget https://example.com/file.txt
19. df: Display disk space usage.
Example: df -h (displays disk space usage in a human-readable format)
20. man: Display the manual for a command.
Example: man ls (displays the manual page for the &quot;ls&quot; command)
21. Start a service:
Example: sudo systemctl start service_name For instance, to start the Apache
web server, you&#39;d use sudo systemctl start apache2.
22. Stop a service:
Example: sudo systemctl stop service_name For instance, to stop the Apache web
server, you&#39;d use sudo systemctl stop apache2.
23. Restart a service:
Example: sudo systemctl restart service_name For instance, to restart the
Apache web server, you&#39;d use sudo systemctl restart apache2.

24. Enable a service to start on boot:
Example: sudo systemctl enable service_name For instance, to enable the
Apache web server to start automatically on boot, you&#39;d use sudo systemctl
enable apache2.
25. Disable a service from starting on boot:
Example: sudo systemctl disable service_name For instance, to disable the
Apache web server from starting automatically on boot, you&#39;d use sudo systemctl
disable apache2.
26. Check the status of a service:
Example: sudo systemctl status service_name
For instance, to check the status of the Apache web server, you&#39;d use sudo systemctl
status apache2.
27. View the log of a service:
Example: sudo journalctl -u service_name
For instance, to view the log of the Apache web server, you&#39;d use sudo journalctl -u
apache2.
28. List all available units (services, sockets, timers, etc.):
Example: systemctl list-units
29. List all running units:
Example: systemctl list-units --type=service --state=running
30. Reload the configuration of a service without stopping it:
Example: sudo systemctl reload service_name
31. Show failed units:
Example: systemctl --failed
32. Find selected text
grep &quot;grep&quot; example.txt
if case sensitive grep -i &quot;grep&quot; example.txt
